      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Library directors make a sad error in judgment when looking to mega-bookstores for ways to attract patrons (news article, Sept. 2). The next step will be to tailor library collections like a mega-bookstore -- shelves filled only with mainstream books and best sellers.</p>
        <p>Instead of selling coffee and snacks, libraries, to keep themselves visible and vital, should invest in more community services.</p>
        <p>Library advocacy is sorely needed to insure that the government and library directors don't view maintaining library services as ''dipping in the never-ending municipal till.''</p>
        <p>DEL HORNBUCKLE</p>
        <p>New York, Sept. 3, 1997</p>
        <p>The writer is a librarian.</p>
      </block>
